<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2001/TECH/space/08/14/light.pollution/index.html">www.cnn.com/2001/TECH/spa...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
This has become more and more apparent to me the older I get.  I am only 28 but I remember when I was in my teens (living at home) I could lay out in my front yard and SEE the milky way!  From my house, in town (a population of 7000, with about 3 million people living in the St. Louis metro area - 50 mile radius - which I live in).  As I got older I noticed the night sky seemed to have less and less stars.  The milky way that we see is actually just a part of the galaxy we live in.  When I was younger it was a very bright band of stars across the sky.  There were so many stars it would amaze me.  We would lay out there for hours on end and enjoy it.  This summer I have yet to see it in such vivid contrast to the night sky.  Only one night, when it was exceptionally clear, when I was about as far as I could get into the &quot;sticks&quot; of our area was I even able to see the stretch of stars and a good number of others in the sky.<br>
<br>
When my wife and I started looking for our first home 2 years ago one of my only stipulations was to get a home in a small town, relatively distant from others in hopes of seeing the sky better.  I used to be an active amateur astronomer and I wanted to be able to see the wonder of the night sky again.  Personally I hoped to find something in the area, but I was even considering moving back to Nebraska (or to a legislative Dark Sky state like Colorado) if I could get a job somewhere else.<br>
<br>
When we first moved to our town I thought my problems solved.  Other than a couple pesky light poles and obnoxious neighboring home lights I had a relatively dark sky at night, right outside of my home again =)  But that all changed about a year ago (after a year of enjoying it).  About 10 miles down the road is a interstate-side community, they are going through rapid expansion (read: suburban sprawl) like most of the metro area (especially east of the Mississippi of late).  There are 2 major interstates that run through this town (55 and 70) so there are plenty of gas stations and truck stops and restaurants (all or most are open 24/7).  When they built a new truck dealership along the interstate (also houses truck repair and other facilities) they lit it up enough to cause spill over lighting of most of the surrounding area.<br>
<br>
It is absolutely ridiculous how much light escapes into the night sky from that city now (it was only bad before...) and on cloudy nights it is almost like day time when you are in that area.  Hence my skies are not very dark anymore.  I think most people are not very aware of what is occurring.  There are cultures even here in the US that are to the point where they cannot pass down their heritage using the stories of the stars.  Every human being on the planet will eventually be affected by this if we are not careful. **If you are interested I can pass on links about the effects of &quot;light pollution&quot; on humans and animals, as well as sites supporting local dark sky organizations or writings on the subject**<br>
<br>
Besides the loss of history and stories, we lose a valuable tool of reflection and wonder, we lose a sense of something larger than us.  Not having the stars to look at is something I do not ever look forward to.  Almost nightly I at least take a walk around my yard/block or sit on my porch to look at the stars (if I turn off all my inside lights and open my shades I can actually get a 75 degree view of most of the southern sky, I actually play EQ by the moonlight a lot of nights - I love our living room with all it windows... at night =p).  My wife and I used to go to a couple places, blanket in tow, and lay and watch the stars for hours.  This is something I wanted to hand down to my kids and their friends (like one of my friends dad did with us) as they grew up.  But it has become something that is harder and harder to do...<br>
<br>
Sorry to go on and on but the article got me thinking and I wanted to share with my friends...  I feel this is one of many things that should addressed in the future.  It affects all of us as well as animals (ever hear about the flocks of migratory birds getting lost because of the bright city lights?).  It is something most people would not even notice since it is relatively gradual.  It is also something that is not going away.  I tend to be a supporter of planned development, energy conservation (turn the lights off!! =p) and somewhat an environmentalist (albeit not a very adamant one, just respect the world we live in and I am happy).  It makes sense to take care of what we got, one day we may be able to find a new home...  But for the time being this is all we got.<br>
<br>
